p: Phytochemical C8, picrasidine M, has a binding energy of −8.0 kcal/mol. C8 is a β-carboline alkaloid present in Picrasma quassioides. Picrasma quassioides has been reported to have antiviral and antifungal activities [ 28]. Supplementary Figure S4b shows the cathepsin L residues that form hydrogen bonds or π-π stacking interactions with C8. The carboxylic group of residue D162 forms two C-H⋯O type hydrogen bonds with C8. Also, residues M70 and G23 form hydrogen bonds of type C-H⋯S and C-H⋯O, respectively, with C8. Also, the residue W189 forms a face-to-edge type of π-π stacking interaction with C8. Further, C8 forms hydrophobic contacts with residues G23, L69, D162 and W189.
